Herod himself had sent forth and laid hold upon John, and
bound him in prison for the sake of Herodias, his brother
Philip’s wife; for he had married her. For John said unto
Herod, It is not lawful for thee to have thy brother’s wife.
And Herodias set herself against him, and desired to kill
him; and she could not; for Herod feared John, knowing
that he was a righteous and holy man, and kept him safe.
And when he heard him, he was much perplexed; and he
heard him gladly. And when a convenient day was come,
that Herod on his birthday made a supper to his lords, and
the high captains, and the chief men of Galilee; and when
the daughter of Herodias herself came in and danced, she
pleased Herod and them that sat at meat with him; and the
king said unto the damsel, Ask of me whatsoever thou wilt,
and I will give it thee. And he sware unto her, WhatsoeverTHE
